Linux Basics

a. Explain what Linux is and why it is used in cybersecurity.

Answer: Linux is an open-source operating system similar to Windows or macOS, but itâ€™s free, customizable, and highly secure. It runs everything from servers and mobile phones (Android) to embedded systems.

Kernel â†’ the core of Linux, managing hardware and system resources.

Distributions (Distros) â†’ versions of Linux like:

Ubuntu (user-friendly)

Kali Linux (used in cybersecurity)

CentOS, Debian, Red Hat (for servers)

Why Linux is Used in Cybersecurity

Open Source: You can inspect and modify the system â€” transparency helps identify vulnerabilities.

Powerful Command Line (CLI): Tools like nmap, tcpdump, and metasploit work directly in Linux.

Security Control: Fine-grained control over permissions and users.

Server Dominance: Most web servers and cloud systems run Linux.

Tools Availability:

Kali Linux includes hacking and penetration testing tools.

Parrot OS, BlackArch, etc., are also built for ethical hackers.

ðŸ§© Scenario Example:
A penetration tester uses Kali Linux to scan a companyâ€™s network with nmap for open ports, detect vulnerable servers, and report possible exploits â€” something much harder to do efficiently on Windows.

