c. Understand Linux file permissions and users.

Answer: 
1. Understanding Permissions
Each file in Linux has three types of permissions for three categories of users:
| Category     | Description                |
| ------------ | -------------------------- |
| `Owner (u)`  | The user who owns the file |
| `Group (g)`  | Users in the same group    |
| `Others (o)` | Everyone else              |

2. Permission Types
| Symbol | Meaning | Example                          |
| ------ | ------- | -------------------------------- |
| `r`    | Read    | View the file                    |
| `w`    | Write   | Edit or delete the file          |
| `x`    | Execute | Run the file as a program/script |

Example output from ls -l:

-rwxr-xr--


Meaning:

Owner: read, write, execute (rwx)

Group: read, execute (r-x)

Others: read only (r--)

3. Changing Permissions and Ownership

| Command | Description        | Example                      |
| ------- | ------------------ | ---------------------------- |
| `chmod` | Change permissions | `chmod 755 script.sh`        |
| `chown` | Change file owner  | `chown root:root secure.txt` |

ðŸ”¸ Example Explanation:

chmod 755 script.sh means:

Owner â†’ full access (7 = rwx)

Group â†’ read + execute (5 = r-x)

Others â†’ read + execute (5 = r-x)

ðŸ”’ Scenario:
A system admin wants only root to modify a security configuration file:

chown root:root firewall.conf
chmod 600 firewall.conf


Now only the root user can read/write it â€” others canâ€™t even view it.

